===Comparison of Middle Persian and Modern Persian vocabulary===

There are some phonological differences between Middle Persian and New Persian. Initial consonant clusters were very common in Middle Persian (e.g. spās &quot;thanks&quot;). However, New Persian does not allow initial consonant clusters, whereas final consonant clusters are common (e.g. asb &quot;horse&quot;).

1 Since some vowels of Middle Persian did not continue in Modern Persian, a number of homophones were created in New Persian. For example, &quot;šir&quot; and &quot;šer&quot;, meaning &quot;milk&quot; and &quot;lion&quot;, respectively, are now both pronounced &quot;šir&quot;. In this case, the older pronunciation is maintained in Kurdish, Dari and Tajiki Persian.

===Middle Persian cognates in other languages===

There is a number of Persian loanwords in English, many of which can be traced to Middle Persian. The lexicon of Classical Arabic also contains many borrowings from Middle Persian. In such borrowings Iranian consonants that sound foreign to Arabic, &quot;g&quot;, &quot;č&quot;, &quot;p&quot;, and &quot;ž&quot;, have been replaced by &quot;q/k&quot;, &quot;j&quot;, &quot;š&quot;, &quot;f/b&quot;, and &quot;s/z&quot;. The exact Arabic renderings of the suffixes &quot;-ik/-ig&quot; and &quot;-ak/-ag&quot; is often used to deduce the different periods of borrowing. The following is a parallel word list of cognates:

