<doc id="889936" wikidata="Q245457" url="?curid=889936" title="Circulant matrix">
<text>In linear algebra, a circulant matrix is a square matrix in which all rows are composed of the same elements and each row is rotated one element to the right relative to the preceding row. It is a particular kind of Toeplitz matrix.

In numerical analysis, circulant matrices are important because they are diagonalized by a discrete Fourier transform, and hence linear equations that contain them may be quickly solved using a fast Fourier transform. They can be interpreted analytically as the integral kernel of a convolution operator on the cyclic group formula_1 and hence frequently appear in formal descriptions of spatially invariant linear operations. This property is also critical in modern software defined radios, which utilize Orthogonal Frequency Division Multiplexing to spread the symbols (bits) using a cyclic prefix. This enables the channel to be represented by a circulant matrix, simplifying channel equalization in the frequency domain.

In cryptography, a circulant matrix is used in the MixColumns step of the Advanced Encryption Standard.

==Definition==

An formula_2 circulant matrix formula_3 takes the form
formula_4
or the transpose of this form (by choice of notation). If each formula_5 is a formula_6 square matrix, then the formula_7 matrix formula_3 is called a block-circulant matrix.

A circulant matrix is fully specified by one vector, formula_9, which appears as the first column (or row) of formula_3. The remaining columns (and rows, resp.) of formula_3 are each cyclic permutations of the vector formula_9 with offset equal to the column (or row, resp.) index, if lines are indexed from formula_13 to formula_14. (Cyclic permutation of rows has the same effect as cyclic permutation of columns.) The last row of formula_3 is the vector formula_9 shifted by one in reverse.

Different sources define the circulant matrix in different ways, for example as above, or with the vector formula_9 corresponding to the first row rather than the first column of the matrix; and possibly with a different direction of shift (which is sometimes called an anti-circulant matrix).

The polynomial formula_18 is called the &quot;associated polynomial&quot; of the matrix formula_3.

== Properties ==

=== Eigenvectors and eigenvalues ===

The normalized eigenvectors of a circulant matrix are the Fourier modes, namely,
