==Analytic interpretation==
Circulant matrices can be interpreted geometrically, which explains the connection with the discrete Fourier transform.

Consider vectors in formula_62 as functions on the integers with period formula_22, (i.e., as periodic bi-infinite sequences: formula_64) or equivalently, as functions on the cyclic group of order formula_22 (denoted formula_1 or formula_67) geometrically, on (the vertices of) the regular: this is a discrete analog to periodic functions on the real line or circle.

Then, from the perspective of operator theory, a circulant matrix is the kernel of a discrete integral transform, namely the convolution operator for the function formula_68; this is a discrete circular convolution. The formula for the convolution of the functions formula_69 is
: formula_70
(recall that the sequences are periodic)
which is the product of the vector formula_71 by the circulant matrix for formula_72.

The discrete Fourier transform then converts convolution into multiplication, which in the matrix setting corresponds to diagonalization.

The formula_73-algebra of all circulant matrices with complex entries is isomorphic to the group formula_73-algebra of formula_75

==Symmetric circulant matrices==
For a symmetric circulant matrix formula_3 one has the extra condition that formula_77. 
Thus it is determined by formula_78 elements. 
formula_79

The eigenvalues of any real symmetric matrix are real.
The corresponding eigenvalues formula_80 become:
formula_81
for formula_22 even, and
formula_83
for formula_22 odd, where formula_85 denotes the real part of formula_86.
This can be further simplified by using the fact that formula_87 and formula_88 depending on formula_89 even or odd.

Symmetric circulant matrices belong to the class of bisymmetric matrices.

==Hermitian circulant matrices==
The complex version of the circulant matrix, ubiquitous in communications theory, is usually Hermitian. In this case formula_90 and its determinant and all eigenvalues are real.

If &quot;n&quot; is even the first two rows necessarily takes the form
