in which the first element formula_92 in the top second half-row is real.

If &quot;n&quot; is odd we get
formula_93

Tee has discussed constraints on the eigenvalues for the Hermitian condition.

== Applications ==

===In linear equations===

Given a matrix equation
: formula_94
where formula_3 is a circulant matrix of size formula_22, we can write the equation as the circular convolution
formula_97
where formula_98 is the first column of formula_3, and the vectors formula_98, formula_101 and formula_102 are cyclically extended in each direction. Using the circular convolution theorem, we can use the discrete Fourier transform to transform the cyclic convolution into component-wise multiplication
formula_103
so that
formula_104

This algorithm is much faster than the standard Gaussian elimination, especially if a fast Fourier transform is used.

=== In graph theory ===

In graph theory, a graph or digraph whose adjacency matrix is circulant is called a circulant graph/digraph. Equivalently, a graph is circulant if its automorphism group contains a full-length cycle. The Möbius ladders are examples of circulant graphs, as are the Paley graphs for fields of prime order.

